recordings.rmk:
Very interesting: 5, 4, then 6 , at least 3 Starlings sit together in the sun on the little roof of a nisting box , and two or three sing together with a lot of typical imitations. They like best to imitate the Northern Lapwing, the Red Kite and the Eurasian Golden Oriole - both, his raugh call and his whistling song, even in variation. 
Young Starlings in the nisting box are to hear at the end of the recording..
Other nisting boxes around.
Imitations from: 
Eurasian Blackcap (00:07, 01:11, 01:22); Northern Lapwing: 00:15;  00:34 Oriole, followed from Common Buzzard;  00:44 Northern Lapwing, Red Kite, Northern Lapwing;  Black Kite (01:14);  Red Kite (01:28); Northern Lapwing (01:36); Common Cuckoo (01:37);  Oriole (01:45);  2:00 electronic ringing ??, followed from Black Kite's call, transformed into Red Kite's call;  Oriole (02:12); Red Kite (02:23); Oriole (02:32); Common Cuckoo (2:37);  from 02:41 a serie of Oriole whistlings (variations) and calls; Barn Swallow; Kestrel (03:04); Oriole (03:20); Red Kite (03:42); Northern Lapwing (3:55);  04:03: Red Kite, followed from Northern Lapwing, Red Kite, begging young Starlings inside the n.box

Starling sit in a dense overgrown tree - this function as a night and day roost and resting point for the local breeding starlings (typical 30-40 a day - occasionally up to 400). So many 'weird' calls are heard from here - and good number of imitation - some years they favor bee-eaters, some years waders or a song bird (icterine warbler, wood warbler) or human devices mobile phone – a truck reversing.But one thing is certain and that is they are fast learners - a bee-eater passes by and a minute later they have it in there song - sometimes for days - which is 'frustrating'.

In this recording a Starling seems to 'wind itself up' and then deliver two impersonations. The first is a car alarm (of a type that the bird would have heard locally) and the second is a rendering derived from Hooded Crow, possibly the predator-alarm guttural 'grik, grik' used when a Hooded Crow has spotted a Sparrowhawk. On the other hand, the Starling may be imitating the standard two- or (as on this recording) three-syllable caw of Hooded Crow and Carrion Crow, although the speed of delivery sounds a bit fast and, therefore, more like the pace of the 'grik, grik' Sparrowhawk alert. The clip starts with a standard single note [0:02] of a type that is used by Starlings when they are piqued. In short measure, an accelerated series of eight 'piqued notes' develop [from 0:04 for two seconds] and a climax is reached at 0:07 that descends into an amazing utterance that vaguely recalls a taut rubber band. By 0:09 (and for almost the next two seconds) vocalisations grow ever-more ecstatic and starting at 0:12 the bird delivers three copies of a car alarm. At 0:14 it switches and mimics a Hooded Crow. From 0:19 onwards it reverts to normal Starling vocabulary and utters bubbling, rattling flutters. 

A three-minute Starling recording containing more information is here: XC213059. 

Also on the recording: within the first two seconds, Blackbirds making social 'toots' (several Blackbirds were present, only a few were calling). Robin ticking calls can be heard at 0:01, 0:23. 0:27 and 0:29.
Note: introduced population. Two series of squawks, presumably some kind of interaction call.

recordings.type: alarm call, begging call, call, hatchling or nestling
recordings.rmk:
The track opens with adult starling calls and house sparrows in the background. There are also some quiet calls from the starling nestlings. From 0:32.5 a starling lands at its nest in a roof and begging calls are heard from the nestlings until the adult leaves again at 0:43.
The nestlings continue to call, but more quietly once the adult has left - these are difficult to hear as a house sparrow is calling. I believe it is an adult starling which calls at 1:11.9. At 1:18.3 a bird, possibly a blackbird, gives a high pitched descending "seee" call as it becomes aware of danger (possibly a sparrowhawk). 
The starling becomes aware at 1:25 and gives a series of calls in alarm, during which time a house sparrow also changes its call. 
The starling returns to the nest at 1:40.3 and the nestlings call for food again. The adult starling leaves the nest once more at 1:50.5 and we are left hearing mainly house sparrow sounds again. The starling appears to briefly return at 2:58.3 but begging calls are not heard. I think the sound from 3:03.4 is a sparrow returning to its nest close by with sparrow begging calls concluding the recording.


Recorded with an Olympus LS-12 and Sennheiser ME66 on a tripod about 3m from the starling's nest. No editing other that a very small deamplification so that the peak is a -3 dB (the peak did not reach 0 dB so should not be clipped).
